[src:history-api/api-history-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] The **History API** provides access to the browser's session history (not to be confused with WebExtensions history) through the `history` global object.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] It exposes useful methods and properties that let you navigate back and forth through the user's history, and manipulate the contents of the history stack.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] Moving backward and forward through the user's history is done using the `back()`, `forward()`, and `go()` methods.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] This acts exactly as if the user clicked on the **Back** button in their browser toolbar.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] You can use the `go()` method to load a specific page from session history, identified by its relative position to the current page.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] Similarly, you can move forward 2 pages by passing `2`, and so forth.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] Allows manipulation of the browser *session history* (that is, the pages visited in the tab or frame that the current page is loaded in).
[src:history-api/api-history-api] The following example assigns a listener for the `popstate` event.
[src:history-api/api-history-api] It then illustrates some of the methods of the history object to add, replace, and move within the browser history for the current tab.
[src:history-api/api-history] The **`History`** interface of the History API allows manipulation of the browser *session history*, that is the pages visited in the tab or frame that the current page is loaded in.
[src:history-api/api-history] There is only one instance of `history` (It is a *singleton*.) accessible via the global object `history`.
[src:history-api/api-history] Returns an `Integer` representing the number of elements in the session history, including the currently loaded page.
[src:history-api/api-history] For example, for a page loaded in a new tab this property returns `1`.
[src:history-api/api-history] Allows web applications to explicitly set default scroll restoration behavior on history navigation.
[src:history-api/api-history] This property can be either `auto` or `manual`.
[src:history-api/api-history] Returns an `any` value representing the state at the top of the history stack.
[src:history-api/api-history] This is a way to look at the state without having to wait for a `popstate` event.
[src:history-api/api-history] This asynchronous method goes to the previous page in session history, the same action as when the user clicks the browser's Back button.
[src:history-api/api-history] Calling this method to go back beyond the first page in the session history has no effect and doesn't raise an exception.
[src:history-api/api-history] This asynchronous method goes to the next page in session history, the same action as when the user clicks the browser's Forward button; this is equivalent to `history.go(1)`.
[src:history-api/api-history] Calling this method to go forward beyond the most recent page in the session history has no effect and doesn't raise an exception.
[src:history-api/api-history] Asynchronously loads a page from the session history, identified by its relative location to the current page, for example `-1` for the previous page or `1` for the next page.
[src:history-api/api-history] If you specify an out-of-bounds value (for instance, specifying `-1` when there are no previously-visited pages in the session history), this method silently has no effect.
[src:history-api/api-history] Calling `go()` without parameters or a value of `0` reloads the current page.
[src:history-api/api-history] Pushes the given data onto the session history stack with the specified title (and, if provided, URL).
[src:history-api/api-history] The data is treated as opaque by the DOM; you may specify any JavaScript object that can be serialized.
[src:history-api/api-history] Note that all browsers but Safari currently ignore the *title* parameter.
[src:history-api/api-history] For more information, see Working with the History API.
[src:history-api/api-history] Updates the most recent entry on the history stack to have the specified data, title, and, if provided, URL.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] The **`pushState()`** method of the `History` interface adds an entry to the browser's session history stack.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] The `state` object is a JavaScript object which is associated with the new history entry created by `pushState()`.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] Whenever the user navigates to the new `state`, a `popstate` event is fired, and the `state` property of the event contains a copy of the history entry's `state` object.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] The `state` object can be anything that can be serialized.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] This parameter exists for historical reasons, and cannot be omitted; passing an empty string is safe against future changes to the method.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] Note that the browser won't attempt to load this URL after a call to `pushState()`, but it may attempt to load the URL later, for instance, after the user restarts the browser.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] The new URL does not need to be absolute; if it's relative, it's resolved relative to the current URL.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] The new URL must be of the same origin as the current URL; otherwise, `pushState()` will throw an exception.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] If this parameter isn't specified, it's set to the document's current URL.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] Thrown if the associated document is not fully active, or if the provided `url` parameter is not a valid URL, or if the method is called too frequently.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] Thrown if the provided `state` parameter is not serializable.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] In a sense, calling `pushState()` is similar to setting `window.location = "#foo"`, in that both will also create and activate another history entry associated with the current document.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] Note that `pushState()` never causes a `hashchange` event to be fired, even if the new URL differs from the old URL only in its hash.
[src:history-api/history-pushstate] This creates a new browser history entry setting the *state* and *url*.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] The **`popstate`** event of the `Window` interface is fired when the active history entry changes while the user navigates the session history.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] It changes the current history entry to that of the last page the user visited or, if `history.pushState()` has been used to add a history entry to the history stack, that history entry is used instead.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Returns a copy of the information that was provided to `pushState()` or `replaceState()`.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If the history entry being activated was created by a call to `history.pushState()` or was affected by a call to `history.replaceState()`, the `popstate` event's `state` property contains a copy of the history entry's state object.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] These methods and their corresponding events can be used to add data to the history stack which can be used to reconstruct a dynamically generated page, or to otherwise alter the state of the content being presented while remaining on the same `Document`.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Note that just calling `history.pushState()` or `history.replaceState()` won't trigger a `popstate` event.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] The `popstate` event will be triggered by doing a browser action such as a click on the back or forward button (or calling `history.back()` or `history.forward()` in JavaScript).
[src:history-api/popstate-event] It's important to first understand that — to combat unwanted pop-ups — browsers may not fire the `popstate` event at all unless the page has been interacted with.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] This section describes the steps that browsers follow in the cases where they *do* potentially fire the `popstate` event (that is, in the cases where the page has been interacted with).
[src:history-api/popstate-event] When a navigation occurs — either due to the user triggering the browser's Back button or otherwise — the `popstate` event is near the end of the process to navigate to the new location.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] It happens after the new location has loaded (if needed), displayed, made visible, and so on — after the `pageshow` event is sent, but before the persisted user state information is restored and the `hashchange` event is sent.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] To better understand when the `popstate` event is fired, consider this simplified sequence of events that occurs when the current history entry changes due to either the user navigating the site or the history being traversed programmatically.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Here, the transition is changing the current history entry to one we'll refer to as **new-entry**.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] The current page's session history stack entry will be referred to as **current-entry**.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If **current-entry**'s title wasn't set using one of the History API methods (`pushState()` or `replaceState()`), set the entry's title to the string returned by its `document.title` attribute.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If the browser has state information it wishes to store with the **current-entry** before navigating away from it, it then does so.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] The entry is now said to have "persisted user state." This information the browser might add to the history session entry may include, for instance, the document's scroll position, the values of form inputs, and other such data.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If **new-entry** has a different `Document` object than **current-entry**, the browsing context is updated so that its `document` property refers to the document referred to by **new-entry**, and the context's name is updated to match the context name of the now-current document.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Each form control within **new-entry**'s `Document` that has `autocomplete` configured with its autofill field name set to `off` is reset.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] See The HTML autocomplete attribute for more about the autocomplete field names and how autocomplete works.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If **new-entry**'s document is already fully loaded and ready—that is, its `readyState` is `complete`—and the document is not already visible, it's made visible and the `pageshow` event is fired at the document with the `PageTransitionEvent`'s `persisted` attribute set to `true`.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] The document's `URL` is set to that of **new-entry**.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If the history traversal is being performed with replacement enabled, the entry immediately prior to the destination entry (taking into account the `delta` parameter on methods such as `go()`) is removed from the history stack.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If the **new-entry** doesn't have persisted user state and its URL's fragment is non-`null`, the document is scrolled to that fragment.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Next, **current-entry** is set to **new-entry**.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] The destination entry is now considered to be current.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If **new-entry** has serialized state information saved with it, that information is deserialized into `History.state`; otherwise, `state` is `null`.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If the value of `state` changed, the `popstate` event is sent to the document.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Any persisted user state is restored, if the browser chooses to do so.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] If the original and new entries shared the same document, but had different fragments in their URLs, send the `hashchange` event to the window.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] As you can see, the `popstate` event is nearly the last thing done in the process of navigating pages in this way.
[src:history-api/popstate-event] Note that even though the original history entry (for `http://example.com/example.html`) has no state object associated with it, a `popstate` event is still fired when we activate that entry after the second call to `history.back()`.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] All major browsers have a private browsing mode in which browsing history is not recorded.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] This is to protect against browsing history being collected by third parties for targeted advertising or other purposes.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Locally stored browsing history can facilitate rediscovering lost previously visited web pages of which one only has a vague memory in mind, or pages difficult to find due to being located within deep web.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Browsers also utilize it to enable autocompletion in their address bar for quicker and more convenient navigation to frequently visited pages.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] The retention span of browsing history varies depending on the web browser.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] An indefinite history file named `Archived History` was once recorded, but has been removed and automatically deleted in version 37, released in September 2014.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Browser extensions such as *History Trends Unlimited* for Google Chrome (desktop version) allow the indefinite local storage of browsing history, exporting into a portable file, and self-analysis of browsing habits and statistics.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Browsing history is not recorded when using the private browsing mode provided by most browsers.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Targeted advertising means presenting the user with advertisements that are more relevant to one based on one's browsing history.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] A typical example is a user receiving advertisements on shoes when browsing other websites after searching for shoes on shopping websites.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] One research shows that targeted advertising doubles the conversion rate of classical online advertising.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Real-time bidding (RTB) is the method used behind targeted advertising.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] It is a system that automatically bids up the price for presenting advertisements on certain websites.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Advertisers decide how much they are willing to pay based on the target audience of the websites.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Therefore, more information about the users could encourage advertisers to pay higher prices.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] The information of users, such as browsing history, is provided to all firms that are involved in the bidding.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Since it is a real-time process, information is usually collected without the consent of the user and transferred in unencrypted form.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] The user has very limited knowledge of how their information is collected, stored, and used.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] The response of the user towards targeted advertising depends on whether one knows the information is being collected.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] If the user already knows that the information is being collected ahead of time, the targeted advertisement could potentially create a positive effect, leading to a higher intention of clicking through the link.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] However, if the user is not informed about information collection, one would be more concerned with privacy.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] This will decrease one's intention of clicking through the link.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Meanwhile when the user considers the website reliable, it is more possible for them to click through the link and accept the personalization service.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] To solve the conflicts between privacy and profits, one newly proposed system is pay-per-tracking.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] A broker exists between users and advertisers.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Users could decide whether to provide their personal information to the broker and then the broker would send the personal information offered by users to advertisers.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Meanwhile, users could receive monetary rewards for sharing their personal information.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] This could help protect the privacy and tracking efficiency, but would lead to extra cost.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Personalized pricing is based on the idea that if a user purchases a certain product frequently or pays a higher price for that product, the user could be charged a higher price for this product.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Web browsing history could give reliable predictions on the purchasing behaviors of users.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When using personalized pricing, the profit of firms could increase by 12.99% compared to status quo cases.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Web browsing history could be used to facilitate research, such as revealing the browsing behavior of people.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When a user browses extensively on one site, the probability of requesting an additional page increases.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When a user visits more sites, the likelihood of requesting extra pages is reduced.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Web browsing history could also be used to create personal web libraries.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] A personal web library is created by collecting and analyzing the web browsing history of the user.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] It could help the user to notice browsing trends, time distribution, and the most frequently used websites.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Some users regard this function as helpful.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Web browsing history stored locally is not published anywhere publicly by default.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] However, almost all the websites are tracked by adwares and potentially unwanted programs (PUPs) which collect users' information without their consent.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] These tracking methods are usually allowed by platforms by default.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Web browsing history is also collected by cookies on websites, which could be divided into two kinds, first-party cookies and third-party cookies.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Third-party cookies are usually embedded on first-party websites and collect information from them.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Third-party cookies have higher efficiency and data aggregation ability than first-party cookies.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] While first-party cookies only have access to users' data on one website, third-party cookies could combine data collected from different websites to make the image of the user more complete.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Meanwhile, several third-party cookies could exist on the same website.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] With enough information available, users could be identified without logging into their accounts.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When third-party cookies collect the web browsing history of users from multiple websites, more information leads to more privacy concerns.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] For example, a user browses news on one website and searches for medical information on the other website.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When the web browsing history from these two websites is combined, the user may be considered interested in news related to medical topics.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When browsing history from different websites is combined, it could reflect a more complete image of the person.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] In 2006, AOL released a large amount of data of its users, including search history.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Although no user IDs or names was included, users could be identified based on the browsing history released.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] 4417749 was identified with her search history over three months.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] In 2020, Avast, a popular antivirus software, has been accused of selling browsing history to third parties.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] It is under preliminary investigation of this accusation by officials of the Czech Republic.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] The report shows that Avast sold users' data through Jumpshot, a marketing analytics tool.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Avast claimed that users' personal information was not included in the leak.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] However, browsing history could be used to identify users.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Avast shut down Jumpshot as a reply to this issue.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When the user feels there is a risk to privacy, one's intention of disclosing personal information will be lower, but the actions are not affected.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] However, some studies find that there is no significant difference between the intention and the actions of disclosing private information, meaning the user will reduce actions of sharing personal information and take more protection measures when feeling concerned about privacy.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] When users have privacy concerns, they would make less use of online services.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] They would also make more protection measures such as refusing to offer their information, offering false information, removing their information online and complaining to people around them or relevant organizations.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] However, it is hard for users to protect their privacy due to multiple reasons.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] First, users do not have enough privacy awareness.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] They are not concerned about being tracked unless there are substantial impacts on them.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] They are also not aware of how their data contains commercial values.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] It is generally difficult for users to notice privacy policy links on all kinds of websites, with female users and older users, being more likely to ignore these notices.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Even when users notice privacy links, their information disclosure may not be affected.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] In addition, users are also not equipped with enough technical knowledge to protect themselves even when they notice privacy leakage.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] They are placed on the passive side with little room to change the situation.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Most users make use of ad blockers, delete cookies, and avoid websites that collect personal information to try to protect their web browsing history from being collected.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] However, most ad blockers do not offer enough guidance to users to help them improve their privacy awareness.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] More importantly, they rely on standard black and white list.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] These lists do not usually include the websites that are tracking users.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] Ad blockers could only be effective if these tracking domains are blocked.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] There are a series of open source projects that try to protect their privacy through collecting their browsing history on the hard drive instead of the browser.
[src:history-api/web-browsing-history] It solves the issue of such as that users cannot see the browsing history data once the user deletes the data on the browser.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] A central theme in web design is the development of a web navigation interface that maximizes usability.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] A website overall navigational scheme includes several navigational pieces such as global, local, supplemental, and contextual navigation; all of these are vital aspects of the broad topic of web navigation.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Hierarchical navigation systems are vital as well since it is the primary navigation system.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] It allows for the user to navigate within the site using levels alone, which is often seen as restricting and requires additional navigation systems to better structure the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] The global navigation of a website, as another segment of web navigation, serves as the outline and template in order to achieve an easy maneuver for the users accessing the site, while local navigation is often used to help the users within a specific section of the site.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] All these navigational pieces fall under the categories of various types of web navigation, allowing for further development and for more efficient experiences upon visiting a web page.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Web navigation came about with the introduction of the World Wide Web in 1989, when Tim Berners-Lee invented it.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Once the World Wide Web was available, web navigation increasingly became a major aspect and role in jobs and everyday lives.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] With one-third of the world’s population now using the Internet, web navigation maintains a global use in today's ever evolving international society.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Web navigation is not restricted to just computers, either, as mobile phones and tablets have added avenues for access to the ever-growing information on the Web today.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] The most recent wave of technology which has affected web navigation is the introduction and growth of the smartphone.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Web navigation has evolved from a restricted action, to something that many people across the world now do on a daily basis.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] The use of website navigation tools allow for a website's visitors to experience the site with the most efficiency and the least incompetence.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] A website navigation system is analogous to a road map which enables web page visitors to explore and discover different areas and information contained within the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] The structure of the website navigation is built from general to specific.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] This provides a clear, simple path to all the web pages from anywhere on the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Global website navigation shows the top level sections/pages of the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] It is available on each page and lists the main content sections/pages of the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Local navigation is the links within the text of a given web page, linking to other pages within the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Web navigations vary in styles between different website as well as within a certain site.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] The availability of different navigational styles allows for the information in the website to be delivered easily and directly.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] This also differentiates between categories and the sites themselves to indicate what the vital information is and to enable the users access to more information and facts discussed within the website.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Across the globe, different cultures prefer certain styles for web navigations, allowing for a more enjoyable and functional experience as navigational styles expand and differentiate.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] What makes web design navigation difficult to work with is that it can be so versatile.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Navigation varies in design through the presence of a few main pages in comparison to multi-level architecture.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Content can also vary between logged-in users and logged-out users and more.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Because navigation has so many differences between websites, there are no set guidelines or to-do lists for organizing navigation.
[src:history-api/web-navigation] Designing navigation is all about using good information architecture, and expressing the model or concept of information used in activities requiring explicit details of complex systems.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] The History API enables a website to interact with the browser's session history: that is, the list of pages that the user has visited in a given window.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] As the user visits new pages, for example by clicking links, those new pages are added to the session history.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] The user can also move back and forth through the history using the browser's "Back" and "Forward" buttons.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] In this guide, we'll cover only the second set of methods.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] The `pushState()` method adds a new entry to the session history, while the `replaceState()` method updates the session history entry for the current page.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Both these methods take a `state` parameter which can contain any serializable object.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] When the browser navigates to this history entry, the browser fires a `popstate` event, which contains the state object associated with that entry.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] The main purpose of these APIs is to support websites like Single-page applications, that use JavaScript APIs such as `fetch()` to update the page with new content, instead of loading a whole new page.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Traditionally, websites are implemented as a collection of pages.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] When users navigate to different parts of the site by clicking links, the browser loads a whole new page each time.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] For these reasons, a popular pattern for web apps is the single-page application (SPA).
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] In this click handler, if the link contains a data attribute `"data-creature"`, then we use the value of that attribute to fetch a JSON file containing the new content for the page.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] The problem is that it breaks the expected behavior of the browser's "Back" and "Forward" buttons.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] From the user's point of view, they clicked a link and the page updated, so it looks like a new page.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] If they then press the browser's "Back" button, they expect to go to the state before they clicked the link.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] But as far as the browser is concerned, the last link didn't load a new page, so "Back" will take the browser to whichever page was loaded before the user opened the SPA.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] This is essentially the problem that `pushState()`, `replaceState()`, and the `popstate` event solve.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] They enable us to synthesize history entries, and to be notified when the current session history entry changes to one of these entries (for example, because the user pressed the "Back" or "Forward" buttons).
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Clicks another link in our SPA, so we update the page and add history entry B using `pushState()`.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Now the new current history entry is A, so the browser fires the `popstate` event, and the event handler argument includes the JSON that we passed to `pushState()` when we handled the navigation to A.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] When the user loads the SPA, the browser adds a history entry.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Because this was an actual page load, the entry has no state associated with it.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Clicks a link inside the SPA, so the click handler updates the page and adds a history entry with `pushState()`.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] Now we want to go back to the SPA's initial state, but since this is a navigation in the same document, the page will not be reloaded, and since the history entry for the initial page has no state, we can't use `popstate` to restore it.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] The solution here is to use `replaceState()` to set the state object for the initial page.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] On page load, we collect all the parts of the page that we need to restore when the user returns to the starting point for the SPA.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] This has the same structure as the JSON we fetch when handling other navigations.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] We pass this `initialState` object into `replaceState()`, which effectively adds the state object to the current history entry.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] When the user returns to our starting point, the `popstate` event will contain this initial state, and we can use our `displayContent()` function to update the page.
[src:history-api/working-with-the-history-api] You can find this complete example at https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/history-api, and see the demo live at https://mdn.github.io/dom-examples/history-api/.
